<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 92 / International Company News: Nikkei decline triggers warning
on Japan banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A JAPANESE banking industry leader yesterday expressed concern that the
country's hard-pressed banks would face difficulties meeting international
standards for capital adequacy.
The recent plunge in the Tokyo stock market would make it difficult for
Japanese banks to meet rules set down by the Bank for International
Settlements, said Mr Kenichi Suematsu, chairman of the Federation of
Bankers' Associations of Japan.
Mr Suematsu's comments, although cautiously framed, were a blunt assessment
of Japanese banks' prospects of meeting standards that will come into effect
in March 1993.
Under BIS rules, Japanese banks are allowed to count as capital a portion of
unrealised gains on stock portfolios. However, the fall in equities has
wiped away much of these profits.
The Nikkei index of leading shares closed yesterday at 17,439.58, up 202.93
points, but down more than 50 per cent from its peak.
Mr Suematsu, who is also president of Sakura Bank, said that banks would be
likely to meet the BIS standard of an 8 per cent capital-to-assets ratio -
as long as the Nikkei rebounded to 20,000.
However, banks could not reach a ratio of 8.5 per cent - allowing a margin
of safety - unless the Nikkei recovered to 23,000.
Asked whether banks would cut loans to meet BIS standards, Mr Suematsu said
it was more natural for banks to try to increase capital and to attempt to
cut assets other than loans - for example, currency-dealing operations.
He added that the current weak demand for loans in Japan was helping banks
reach their desired ratios.
Mr Suematsu's remarks beg the question of what might happen if banks fail to
meet BIS ratios. The international agreement covering capital adequacy
carries no sanctions and is not binding on the countries that signed it, let
alone on individual banks. It is left to the regulatory authorities in each
country to decide what to do with banks that fail to meet the standards. In
Japan, this means the Ministry of Finance.
Given the complexity of the rules determining how to account for assets and
capital, the ministry has some flexibility. However, it could not bend
regulations blatantly since this could arouse complaints from other
countries. It would also undermine confidence in the banks - and so be
counter-productive.
However, as IBCA, a London-based rating agency, says in a report it would be
in nobody's interest for the Ministry of Finance to become 'rigidly
doctrinaire' and demand that banks should reach BIS standards whatever the
cost.
To a large extent, BIS has already achieved its purpose in devising the
ratios. The mere publication of the data has forced banks to be more prudent
in managing their assets - well before the rules formally come into effect.
US and European banks, which hoped the rules would curb the runaway
international expansion of Japanese banks, have also seen their aim
fulfilled, albeit more drastically than they had expected.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
