<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 92 / Capital spending rise seen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAPITAL spending by small companies in Britain rose 37 per cent in the
second half of last year, following two half-year periods of steep decline,
according to National Westminster Bank's small business investment index
published yesterday.
However, part of the increase came from businesses switching from overdrafts
to term loans. Excluding this factor the underlying upward trend was less
pronounced and did not mark a significant improvement in business
confidence, the bank said.
The rise in capital spending in the second half of last year was still only
half the level of early 1988.
The strongest recovery was in the Midlands and Wales where capital spending
rose 46 per cent compared with the first half of last year. Spending in the
south-west rose 41 per cent while the weakest upturn - 27 per cent - was in
north England.
The sharpest upturn in spending by investment category occurred in working
capital and stock. Spending rose by about 33 per cent, though from a very
low base.
The index is based on lending made under NatWest's Business Development Loan
Scheme.
</TEXT>
