<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 92 / Fourth win bolsters hopes of long careers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS THE new junior ministers enter their departments for their first full day
in office today many are looking forward to long ministerial careers.
The fourth Conservative general election victory has reinforced the belief
among some former Tory backbenchers that they should not tolerate
obstruction from the Sir Humphreys of the Civil Service.
While some of those in the re-shuffle have spent almost their entire careers
in politics, others will bring business experience to bear. As long ago as
last year a few had considered 'management tactics' for their first days in
a department.
One said that though it was usual for junior ministers to go to the
permanent secretary's office to be briefed on arrival, he would insist that
the permanent secretary came to his office for the initial discussion.
He would also insist on senior officials always calling him by his
ministerial title rather than his first name, and would not allow meetings
to be put in his diary without his consent. Prospective ministers are
acutely aware of the danger of becoming bogged down in minutiae, losing
contact with the parliamentary party and lacking time to think
strategically.
Alongside the standard ploy of being particularly difficult and demanding in
the first few weeks, at least one other aspiring minister had in mind a more
detailed campaign for ensuring he got a grip on his department. This
involved identifying the most indiscreet member of his private office -
usually made up of youngish high-flyers  - and finding out which were the
dullest and worst areas of the department.
Armed with this information, he would, within the next few months, provoke a
row with the least satisfactory officials, and secure their transfer to a
backwater. 'Pour encourager les autres,' he said with a smile.
These are plans made before seeing the reality of the red boxes of
government papers. Even once they are familiar with their duties, new
ministers may be surprised at the volume of relatively unimportant but
reasonably urgent decisions they have to take. The number of unforeseen
engagements filling their days, and the briefings and draft speeches
involved, can also come as a shock.
After all, politicians have entered their ministries with brave words
before. Even if destined for long and successful careers, their time in any
junior post may be no more than about 18 months.
According to a recent report by Professor Richard Rose of the University of
Strathclyde, frequent reshuffles made many ministers 'toddlers rather than
veterans' in their departmental responsibilities.
The study said ministers' short terms in office encouraged them to
concentrate on topics that offered short-term popularity and hampered their
ability to direct government - but did make them good political ambassadors
for their departments. Yesterday's appointees have been warned.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
