<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 92 / Babangida sets up Nigerian council of state
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NIGERIA'S President Ibrahim Babangida has established an advisory body
including former military and civilian rulers to help him tackle the
country's problems, state radio said yesterday, Reuter reports from Lagos.
'The newly reconstituted Council of State must. . . be viewed as a
constitutional artifact to help forge a common approach to the challenges of
nation building in our federal system,' Gen Babangida said at the opening on
Monday.
Nigeria's first post-independence head of state, Mr Nnamdi Azikiwe, former
military ruler Gen Yakubu Gowon and the last civilian president, Shehu
Shagari, attended the meeting in Abuja, the capital.
President Babangida said the council of state, which last met in its present
form a decade ago, was expected to smooth the path to a civilian republic by
January 2.
It will seek solutions to economic problems, including a large foreign debt
and heavy dependence on imports.
</TEXT>
