<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 92 / German public service unions call strike vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY'S power struggle over pay has entered a critical phase following the
collapse of negotiations between government and public service unions on
Monday night.
The four main unions involved, representing all public services, yesterday
called strike ballots for next week after rejecting the employers' final
offer of a package worth 4.8 per cent - effectively a wage freeze.
Mr Rudolf Seiters, the interior minister responsible for the employers'
negotiating team, claimed the increase, payable to around 3m employees,
would cost federal, state and local governments an extra DM15bn (Pounds
5.2bn) a year.
Ms Monika Wulf-Mathies, president of the oTV union, the second largest after
the engineers' IG Metall, said the employers' proposal was an encouragement
to strike.
The offer came during resumed talks after an arbitration panel last week
proposed - and employers rejected  - a compromise increase of 5.4 per cent
plus DM600 in back-pay and holiday allowances.
The oTV, with 1.25m members, is the main force in the public services
sector. It represents a wide range of local authority employees, including
dustmen, nurses, bus and tram drivers, power and water workers. The three
other unions involved represent white collar, federal railway and postal
staff. Results are expected by Friday April 24, and the oTV threatened
immediate stoppages if the necessary 75 per cent vote for action was
achieved.
The employers' position is underpinned by determined resistance from
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Bonn administration, which is committed to strict
controls on public spending and wants all available resources, including
company profits, funneled into the east German economy.
At the personal level, Mr Seiters wants to show his mettle in advance of
this autumn's cabinet reshuffle. Ms Wulf-Mathies, meanwhile, who last year
won a 6 per cent increase for her membership, faces re-election in June when
her 10-year term of office ends.
Wavering public sympathy for union demands has so far tended to favour pay
moderation, although the direct impact of disrupted public services may
influence the mood.
The previous public sector strike, which lasted three chaotic days in
February 1974, ended with employers' capitulation and an 11 per cent pay
award. All services were affected in many large towns. In the Rhineland
Palatinate, power workers cut off the state government's electricity for the
duration.
</TEXT>
