<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 92 / Labour sets July deadline for selection of leadership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OPENING shots in the Labour leadership battle were fired last night as
Mr Bryan Gould found himself with just 12 weeks to halt the bandwagon
rolling for his rival and odds-on favourite, Mr John Smith.
Mr Gould called for a period of reappraisal after the election defeat, while
Mr Smith presented himself as the candidate of continuity.
Both declared their candidacies yesterday while the party's national
executive agreed a compromise July 18 date for the election's conclusion -
later than Mr Smith's supporters wanted, but much earlier than the October
date favoured by the Gould camp.
Mr John Prescott, the transport spokesman, became the third candidate to
enter the race by declaring his bid for the deputy leadership, a post also
being contested by Mr Gould.
Both Mr Smith and Mr Gould called for the fullest possible participation by
union members, including balloting wherever feasible, to complement voting
by MPs and constituency parties.
Mr Smith presented himself as the natural heir to the policy reforms
undertaken by Mr Kinnock. The fundamental task for Labour, he said, would be
to build on the party's principles.
Arguing for policies to convince voters that prosperity is best advanced by
a government which works for the welfare of the whole community, he said:
'Modern government should be pluralistic, decentralised and should be
underpinned by recognition of individual rights.'
Presenting himself as the candidate for change, Mr Gould insisted that the
party needed 'a period of serious reflection about what went wrong and what
needs to be done,' and promised a 'positive and radical agenda.'
''One more heave' may have been the right response to our 1987 defeat,' Mr
Gould said, echoing pundits' claims that Mr Smith was better suited to fight
the election just past than the one to come. 'It is a wholly inadequate
response to our 1992 defeat.'
There are clear differences between the two on economic policy. Mr Gould
said it was necessary to discuss broader issues beyond the 'very narrow
terrain' of tax policy, such as Britain's weighting in the European exchange
rate mechanism.
Mr Smith has always insisted that a Labour government would not tamper with
sterling's exchange rate.
Both stopped short of open support for a new electoral system. While Mr
Smith said he would await the Plant committee's findings, he made clear that
the Labour party 'must be free to reach its own conclusions.'
By contrast, Mr Gould said the conclusion of the Plant committee should
trigger a wider debate with all the political parties and other groups.
Neither candidate would endorse the possibility of an electoral pact or
coalition with the Liberal Democrats.
Mr David Blunkett, the local government spokesman, is acting as Mr Gould's
campaign manager. Mr Robin Cook, the health spokesman, is acting for Mr
Smith.
Unions shun secret ballot for Labour votePage 7 Smith and Gould outline
battle plansPage 7
</TEXT>
