<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / The City Bombing: Challenge to sustain commercial heartbeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROTECTING the image of London's commercial heart was the Corporation of
London's toughest challenge after the explosion that damaged 200 buildings.
The bombing of the Stock Exchange a year ago made it clear to the
Corporation that faith in the City as a place to do business could be shaken
by a terrorist attack.
Within 60 hours of Friday's bomb it had contacted nearly all the 36
companies known to be affected and helped arrange relocation. Yesterday at
9.30am most were operating.
The clubbiness for which the Square Mile is often criticised worked to its
advantage. Mr Peter Tudball, chairman of the Baltic Exchange, could visit
his friend Sir Brian Jenkins, the lord mayor, and brief him over a gin and
tonic.
Sir Brian was able to put him in touch with another friend, Mr David
Coleridge, chairman of Lloyd's, the insurance market, to talk about
alternative accommodation for the Baltic Exchange. Sir Brian said: 'That's
what the City is all about.' Sir Brian was at dinner when police contacted
him about the explosion.
He went to the scene where he met another old friend, Mr Owen Kelly,
commissioner of the City police, who had a list of businesses affected. The
lord mayor passed this to Mr Ted Harthill, the City surveyor, who was able
to put displaced businesses in touch with surveyors who had office space.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
</DOC>
