<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Narrow vote in favour of Rover changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROVER workers have voted by a very narrow margin in favour of reforms to
working practices and bargaining procedures through which the company aims
to transform efficiency. The package has been strongly endorsed by union
leaders.
The vote in the ballot of 28,000 union members was 11,961 to 11,793. While
the company intends to go ahead with the reforms, the narrowness of the vote
suggests that Rover faces a hard task in persuading its workforce to adopt
the changes wholeheartedly.
Union leaders had praised Rover for its willingness to negotiate and for its
attempts to involve workers more fully in decision-making.
Shopfloor resentment is thought to have stemmed in part from the company's
failure to offer any cash inducement to accept the package. Other carmakers
seeking change have tended to make such offers. Rover had sought to sweeten
its package through such measures as increasing job security by suggesting
it would not implement compulsory redundancies, and by improving holiday and
sick-pay arrangements for blue-collar workers.
While welcoming these proposals, some workers were concerned about measures
such as the phasing out of 'clocking-on' arrangements and payment of wages
by credit transfer rather than in cash. The company's intention of removing
all demarcations between jobs will have raised fears about increased
workloads.
Other aspects of the package include 'single-table' bargaining procedures at
which leaders of white-collar and blue-collar unions will negotiate on pay
together; the extension of team working; and a mechanism for binding
arbitration in disputes, providing both sides agree to it.
Rover said the package was so broad that it was inevitable there would be
concerns. It would attempt to allay fears as it introduced the changes.
</TEXT>
