<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / BBC urged to end recognition of unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN END to automatic union recognition by the BBC has been suggested by one
of the internal task forces on the future of the corporation.
The proposal is one of the recommendations of the employers' task force
which recommends that the clause in the BBC's Royal Charter providing for
union recognition should be removed in the new charter which will run from
the beginning of 1997.
The proposals make it clear that the members of the employers' task force
would like the BBC to move towards more direct negotiations with its
employees. Under such a scheme BBC employees would still be able to join
unions. However, those unions fear they could be derecognised for the
purposes of collective bargaining. The introduction of individual personal
contracts has become common in the media industries, particularly in
national newspapers, in recent years.
The proposals on future recognition of unions at the BBC are among those
expected to be leaked by Bectu, the broadcasting union, today.
The union is believed to have detailed information on all of the
recommendations made by the task force. They are due to be considered next
month by the BBC board of man-agement and the governors.
Some individual task-force proposals have already been rejected. One
committee suggested that the corporation should review the potential for
contracting out of BBC services. However, Sir Michael Checkland,
director-general of the BBC, has said that no such policy would be
implemented.
</TEXT>
