FT  14 APR 92 / NHS, Hospital trusts to spend 1.6bn on building improvements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Health Service and hospital trusts are to spend Pounds 1.6bn on
building improvements as a consequence of the lifting of Crown immunity from
hospital properties, a survey of health authorities says, Daniel Green
writes.
Most of the work is to conform with fire regulations. NHS Crown immunity was
lifted a year ago. Until then planning regulations did not apply to
hospitals. One authority has been quoted Pounds 40m to upgrade its five
hospitals.
The Audit Commission yesterday described the findings of the survey as
'reasonable'.
One fifth of health authorities and hospital trusts were asked by Building
Intelligence Digest, a consultancy, how much they planned to spend to
conform to regulations. Nearly two thirds had earmarked Pounds 2m with one
in seven planning to spend more than Pounds 10m.
