<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Builders predict more job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE construction industry has raised its expectations of job losses suffered
in the three-year recession. It fears that more than 300,000 jobs will have
gone by the end of this year in spite of signs that indicators of future
activity are continuing to improve.
Mr John Smith, chairman of the Building Employers Confederation, said
yesterday: 'There is still no sign of renewed growth in output, so 1992 will
be another extremely tough year for construction firms and their employees.'
Mr Smith was commenting on the confederation's latest state-of-trade
inquiry, which gives a gloomy picture of trading prospects for the UK
building industry. Construction output fell 9 per cent last year, but Mr
Smith warned that the consensus of industry forecasts indicating a further
fall in output of between 4 per cent and 5 per cent this year may prove too
optimistic.
Until the end of last year the confederation had expected the fall in
employment since mid 1989 to be between 200,000 and 250,000. But the
recession has forced it to revise its forecast. Mr Smith said: 'The jobless
figure looks like continuing to rise for the rest of 1992 and into 1993.' He
described a reduction of 300,000 jobs as 'disastrous' for the industry
because of the loss of skilled craftsmen.
The confederation draws some encouragement from an easing in the decline of
inquiries for work and from an increase in optimism about future workloads.
Mr Smith also noted optimism among smaller and medium-sized builders
involved in refurbishment work. He was 'greatly concerned', however, that
the amount of work in hand among bigger construction companies continued to
fall. 'I am afraid that this reflects the gradual completion of large
projects which are not being replaced by new orders.' It also emerged from
the inquiry that the proportion of construction companies operating at less
than half capacity has risen to 25 per cent.
Mr Smith urged the government to use the opportunity created by the general
election result to stimulate the housing market by abolishing stamp duty -
which has been temporarily suspended - and to bring more stability to
prices.
The 600 companies involved in the inquiry were taken from the
confederation's 8,000 members. They were asked to list three top priorities
for stimulating construction demand.
Machines in need of maintenance, Page 18
</TEXT>
