FT  14 APR 92 / Call for change in education policy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AN END to the 'vivisection approach' to education policy, and a greater
willingness by parents to pay for school improvements, were yesterday urged
by the leader of a teaching union.
Mrs Heather Ryan, president of Amma - the third-largest teachers' union -
told its annual conference in Birmingham that teachers had 'been forced to
breaking point' by the government's 'muddled planning and impossible
targets, rigidly imposed without thought'.
She added: 'Politicians and Civil Service advisers have approached education
like vivisectionists, using schools as laboratories for doctrinaire
curriculum, assessment and funding techniques, squeezing the life and
creativity out of the education service.'
</TEXT>
