<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Waddington to become governor of Bermuda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD WADDINGTON, who left the cabinet at the weekend, is to become governor
of Bermuda, Downing Street announced yesterday.
The former leader of the House of Lords, who made way for Mr John Wakeham,
the former energy secretary and election campaign 'fixer', will take up his
new post late in the summer. The governorship carries an annual salary
equivalent to Dollars 115,000 (Pounds 65,280).
Mr John Major, the prime minister, spent some time yesterday consulting Mr
Richard Ryder, the chief whip, about the reshuffle of junior ministers. Most
of those changes will be announced today. Other senior colleagues were
consulted on Saturday when the cabinet posts were allocated.
There are about 40 places to be filled. The middle ranks of ministers have
been depleted, both by promotions to the cabinet and by those who have lost
their seats, including Mr Francis Maude, Mr John Maples, Mrs Lynda Chalker
and Mr Michael Fallon.
Among ministers tipped for advancement are Mr Stephen Dorrell, the junior
health minister, Sir George Young, the housing minister, and Mr John
Redwood, the corporate affairs minister. In the Lords, Baroness Blatch, the
environment minister, may also receive promotion.
Of those who are in the whips' office or are parliamentary private
secretaries - the first rung on the ministerial ladder - candidates for
office include Mr William Hague, parliamentary private secretary to Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor, and Mr David Davis, a whip.
Although the new intake of Tory MPs contains many who have already been
associated with the government, such as Mrs Judith Chaplin, who was Mr
Major's political secretary, and Mr David Willetts, who was director of the
Centre for Policy Studies, the rightwing think tank, it is unlikely that any
of those entering the Commons for the first time would be given office
immediately.
</TEXT>
