<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Labour steps back to the good-old bad-old days: Ivo Dawnay
says the party is suffering from a bout of recrimination and self-pity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MR JOHN SMITH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
prematurely hailed as chief architect of an historic Labour victory - found
himself labelled yesterday into a creature of the 'union barons', a
beneficiary of a conspiracy and a stooge of the party establishment.
In the meantime, the election was not lost by Labour, but, according to its
outgoing leader, won by the Tory tabloid press. Only one thing, as they say
in the lager ads, can do this: a Labour election disaster and the onset of a
party leadership contest. Nobody can deny a party's right to a little
recrimination and self-pity in defeat; but then nobody exhibits it so
publicly and with such gothic hyperbole and suicidal skill as Labour.
Yesterday it was like old times. The day began with the claims of Mr Colin
Byrne - until last year Labour's chief press officer - in a letter to The
Guardian.
Mr Byrne charged that Mr Smith had 'cost the party dear' with his tax plans
and sat on his hands through all the tough decision-making of the Kinnock
years.
Unnamed conspirators, he added, 'had been manouvering (sic) John Smith into
position to walk into the leadership should Labour lose and orchestrated the
ruthless undermining and behind-the-hand rubbishing of perceived rivals in a
future contest'.
In other words, over all these years, when people like Mr Byrne were
insisting all was sweetness and light in the Labour team, it had in fact
been business as usual.
Much of this stems from Mr Neil Kinnock's now infamous dinner with
journalists at Luigi's restaurant, Covent Garden, in January. Some in the
Kinnock camp claim Mr Smith's office then briefed against the leader,
contradicting his suggestion that higher tax and National Insurance
contributions might be 'phased-in'.
In this particular demonology, therefore, it is only a small (if simplistic)
leap for the fanatically loyal to claim that it was Mr Smith's intransigence
on tax that lost Labour the election. The truth is probably less
conspiratorial.
Mr Smith was indeed widely believed to have been irritated by his leader's
dinnertime indiscretions, as he wished to keep back the option of phasing in
tax rises should it be needed. But to suggest this was all part of an
elaborate plot aimed at engineering Mr Smith a smooth passage to the Labour
leadership is laughable. Hearing Mr Byrne inveigh against 'spin-doctors' in
his lunchtime interviews yesterday caused a good deal of mirth in the
Commons' press gallery. As Labour's chief press officer for three years
under the communications directorship of Mr Peter Mandelson, Mr Byrne was
himself - arguably quite properly - a professional interpreter of events to
the media.
The second charge against the Smith camp - that it is steamrollering the
shadow chancellor into the leadership - is also only half the story. After
all, it is Mr Kinnock's determination to go that is pressing a quick
decision - although it must be admitted that this is not to Mr Smith's
disadvantage.
As for the role of the 'union barons' in the election, it will be the same
in June or July as it will be in October. There is also an irony in the
outrage among some of Labour's best known leftwingers - some of whom worked
hard to get the unions the biggest possible say in leadership elections at
the expense of MPs and constituency parties - that they intend to exercise
that right.
Is Labour back in the days of fierce ideological schism? It should not be,
yet it is in danger of becoming so. The differences between Mr Bryan Gould
and Mr Smith are complex, but they defy the simple categories of left versus
right.
There are distinct differences on attitudes to Europe and the economy. But
the key to Mr Gould's campaign is going to be putting a case for a new
appeal and a fresh style, aimed at attracting the southern middle-class that
Labour so signally failed to win over last week. His implicit argument in a
weekend interview was that the shadow chancellor had underestimated the poor
reaction to his tax plans among the 'aspiring' classes and that he lacked
the 'zeal and the passion' needed to woo the public away from 'pocket-book
issues'.
Some in the party, however, seem determined to try to transform Mr Gould
into the left's candidate and to portray the more traditional Mr Smith as an
advocate of a no longer valid 'steady-as-she-goes' policy. Mr Ken
Livingstone, the MP for Brent East, was yesterday among several leftwingers
who argued that the rightwing shadow chancellor had been too tough on
middle-income taxpayers.
What is clear is that before the election is held, Mr Smith will have to
fill in the blank sections of his ideological curriculum vitae to counter
the 'lack of vision' charges. So far Mr Smith is known, almost exclusively,
for his cautious bank-manager style.
In some respects it is his misfortune that what now looks more than likely
to be a foreshortened leadership contest will leave him almost inevitably
vulnerable to the accusation that he has been elected by a discredited
system.
His only plausible response to that is to follow Mr Gould's lead and promise
to accelerate changes in the party constitution to ensure that future
elections are conducted on the basis of one member, one vote.
Meanwhile, attention in Westminster has turned to the race for the deputy
leadership, which might be a dress rehearsal for the next leadership battle.
The decision by Mrs Margaret Beckett, shadow chief secretary to the
Treasury, not to run has mystified some of her supporters. With the
advantages of being a woman, English and leftwing, she is the ideal
complement to Scottish Mr Smith and may be persuaded to change her mind.
Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary, is thought certain to run, as
may either or both Mr Gordon Brown and Mr Tony Blair, respectively the trade
and industry and employment spokesmen - and dubbed by the acerbic Mr
Prescott as the 'beautiful people'.
With official declarations expected to begin tomorrow, the triumphant Tories
 -now basking in their election victory - are anticipating a highly
enjoyable summer.
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
