FT  14 APR 92 / Mayhew to meet Irish minister
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Belfast Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Patrick Mayhew, the new Northern Ireland secretary, yesterday made clear
that there was no place at talks on the province's political future for
those who support violence.
In spite of assertions by Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, during
the election campaign that it would have to be included at some stage, Sir
Patrick said: 'The position of the British government has been made
abundantly clear. There never is a place for anybody at any table who
resorts to violence.'
On his first day in office in Belfast Sir Patrick outlined his immediate
priorities. These include meetings as soon as possible with Mr David
Andrews, the Irish foreign affairs minister, and with Northern Ireland's
political leaders. Sir Patrick will also meet unionist and nationalist
leaders.
He is expected to meet Mr Andrews at an Anglo-Irish Conference meeting in
Belfast shortly after Easter. A formal suspension of conference sessions may
be announced at that meeting so that inter-party talks on the future
government of the province can be reconvened.
Unionists have welcomed the appointment of Sir Patrick to the Northern
Ireland office.
The new Ulster secretary was given a series of intensive briefings by
political and security advisers at Stormont Castle yesterday.
Sir Patrick yesterday dismissed potential Nationalist concern over his
alleged refusal to prosecute police officers at the centre of the so-called
shoot-to-kill investigations. The former attorney-general said the decision
had not been his and that he had left the past behind him.
</TEXT>
