<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Activists fear 'union barons' will decide leadership race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SIGHT of union leaders queueing to endorse Mr John Smith as successor to
Mr Neil Kinnock has been 'very bad for Labour's image', Mr Mike Craven, head
of the Labour Co-ordinating Committee, the constituency party pressure
group, said yesterday.
The worry for Mr Craven, and others, is that 'union barons in smoked-filled
rooms' will decide the election after little consultation with their
members, giving further credence to the idea of Labour as a plaything of
unrepresentative union leaders.
The unions, representing 40 per cent of the votes in Labour's electoral
college, prefer Mr Smith as successor to Mr Kinnock. The leadership of three
main unions, the GMB and TGWU general unions and the AEEU, the craft union
merged from the AEU and the EETPU, have already declared for Mr Smith.
However, in spite of the tight timetable, the main unions will probably
ballot their members.
Membership ballots would at least give Mr Bryan Gould, or any other
candidate, the chance to challenge that recommendation. Mr Gould may also
win backing from Nupe, the public-service union, the National Communications
Union and other smaller unions.
In the previous elections the unions have used a wide variety of methods to
consult their members. Some have balloted members. Others have consulted
through union branches, and a third group has left it to their executives or
annual conferences to decide.
Although there now appears to be pressure for balloting, not all unions will
be able to, or want to, conform. The tight timetable makes balloting
difficult to arrange, the cost could be considerable and cannot - like some
other ballots - be recouped from the government.
The MSF technical union will 'consult as widely as possible through the
branches' says Mr Roger Lyons, general-secretary designate. Mr Tony Clarke,
deputy general secretary of the UCW postal union, says: 'We will consult
through branches. A postal ballot would cost Pounds 30,000 and, judging from
union elections, the turnout would be about 20 per cent. Democracy would not
necessarily be served.'
Ballots in the TGWU and the AEEU could cost more than Pounds 100,000. Mr
Nigel Harris, a member of both the AEU executive and Labour's national
executive, supports a quick election. 'I do not think we could have had a
situation in which the party was in limbo for six months,' he said.
</TEXT>
