FT  14 APR 92 / The men Kinnock blames
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Kelvin McKenzie
The Sun
His views were made known in a typically trenchant manner yesterday. An aide
said the claim that the press cost Mr Kinnock his election victory was an
insult to the 14m people who voted Conservative. The Sun says today that the
difference between it and Mr Kinnock is that its message is 'one of good
humour' and his 'one of vindictiveness'.
Sir Nicholas Lloyd
Daily Express
He dismissed Mr Kinnock's remarks about the press as 'a case of sour
grapes'. He said Mr Kinnock had not mentioned the vitriolic campaign mounted
against Mr John Major by the Daily Mirror. Sir Nicholas added: 'He doesn't
mention The Guardian, The Independent - or the Financial Times, which
advised its readers to vote Labour.'
Sir David English
Daily Mail
'The Mail is a campaigning Tory newspaper which examined very closely the
weaknesses of the Labour position and made sure our readers knew about them.
To suggest, as Mr Kinnock has done, that the Daily Mail single-handedly won
the election for the Conservatives . . . ascribes far more influence to us
