<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Ever Ready sold by Hanson for Pounds 123m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HANSON, the Anglo-US conglomerate, has sold Ever Ready, the UK dry cell
battery manufacturer, for Pounds 132m to Ralston Purina, the diversified
US-based food group.
The move was described yesterday by one of Hanson's financial advisers as a
'tidying-up exercise' before making a larger acquisition.
Ralston's purchase of Ever Ready, a brand it already owns in most countries
outside the UK, confirms it as the world's largest manufacturer of dry cell
batteries, adding annual sales of about Dollars 154.1m (Pounds 89.5m) to the
Dollars 1.6bn which its existing battery division reported for the year to
September 30.
The financial adviser also said the exercise was 'aimed at providing the
group with more cash to enable it to pounce on the next big target. I think
that Hanson will now look to sell its 2.8 per cent shareholding in ICI
before making its expected big acquisition'.
There has been speculation that Hanson would sell its ICI holding since Lord
Hanson told shareholders in February that the group had no plans for bidding
for the chemicals group. Hanson bought its shares for an average price of
1,194p, they closed yesterday at 1,315p.
In the long-running debate over Hanson's ability to run companies, the
group's actions at Ever Ready have given ammunition to supporters and
critics alike.
When Hanson bought Berec (which included Ever Ready) in 1981 its profits had
declined to a third of their 1970s peak, partly because it had missed the
shift to long-life alkaline batteries.
Hanson ruthlessly cut costs and sold assets, including most of the European
operations to Duracell, its US competitor. The disposals realised half the
purchase price of Pounds 95m. Operating profits rebounded to a peak of
Pounds 23.4m in 1989 but fell back to Pounds 18.5m in 1991 on sales of
Pounds 87.1m.
But Hanson came to realise in the late 1980s that Ever Ready could flourish
only as a multinational business. Mr Martin Taylor, vice-chairman, said the
group had examined buying Duracell from Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, the Wall
Street firm which had taken it private in a 1988 leveraged buy-out.
Ralston had bought Eveready, the US-based bearer of the famous brand name,
from Union Carbide for Dollars 1.4bn. Hanson has since tried to buy it from
Ralston but failed. 'We originally looked at buying Duracell from KKR and
then looked at acquiring Ralston's battery business. We believe selling Ever
Ready in the UK meets the same objectives.'
Ralston Purina, whose marketshare in the UK was previously around 3 per
cent, claims that its purchase 'fills a major gap' in its geographical
coverage. Its market share in the Dollars 3bn US market is roughly
equivalent to that of Duracell but Ralston has steadily enhanced its
European presence.
Ralston claims that, after the Hanson deal, it leads the European market
overall.
Observer, Page 19
Lex, Page 20
