<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Party row erupts as Kinnock quits: MPs voice opposition to
early leadership contest - 'Tory press' blamed for defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ACRIMONIOUS row broke out within the Labour party yesterday over plans
for a speedy change of leader after Mr Neil Kinnock stepped down following
last week's election defeat.
Several MPs, including Mr Bryan Gould, the shadow environment spokesman and
a likely contender, declared their strong opposition to an early contest
which could see Mr John Smith, the shadow chancellor and odds-on favourite,
elected to succeed Mr Kinnock.
In a sombre statement in his Commons offices, Mr Kinnock blamed what he
called the 'Tory press' for his defeat.
'I make and I seek no excuses, and I express no bitterness when I say that
the Conservative-supporting press has enabled the Tory party to win yet
again when the Conservative party could not have secured victory for itself
on the basis of its record, its programme or its character.'
He told Labour supporters to ignore media coverage of the internal election
which the party must hold to replace him.
'I have only one piece of advice for the Labour movement at every level  -
do not feed and do not believe the press and broadcasting media in their
reporting of these events,' he said.
Tributes to his leadership flowed in from several senior party figures and
included a private message from the prime minister. Mr Kinnock made clear
that he and Mr Roy Hattersley, the deputy leader, would ask a special
meeting of the National Executive Committee today to call the elections for
late June.
Arguing that the date served the 'best interests' of the party, he said the
timetable would allow the parliamentary party to elect a new shadow cabinet
before the summer recess. With the Conservatives holding a small majority
and continuing deep economic difficulties 'it would not be right for the
Labour party to wait six months until October', he said.
Although most MPs on the NEC oppose an early contest, Mr Kinnock's timetable
is likely to be agreed, but the vote will be close. Some unions are
understood to be worried, however, at being seen to 'steamroller' through an
early contest when their dominant role in the process is the subject of
controversy.
The row was fuelled yesterday by a vituperative letter to The Guardian from
Mr Colin Byrne, Labour's chief press officer until last autumn.
Claiming that a hurried contest will cut short a full debate on how to
respond to Labour's election defeat, he wrote that Labour was 'sleepwalking
towards a leadership fix in the grubby old style with ageing trade union
barons, nods and winks about easing up on the accelerator pedal of reform
and smokefilled rooms being the main features'.
Mr Byrne also accused Mr Smith of failing to support Mr Kinnock adequately
in his party reforms. His intervention was interpreted by party insiders as
an effort to open the contest to other potential leadership candidates, not
least Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow trade secretary.
But union leaders differed. Mr Bill Jordan of the engineers' countered that
the need for stability within the party meant the election should be
completed 'as soon as possible'.
The ferocity of the row provoked Mr Jack Cunningham, Labour's campaigns
co-ordinator, to intervene with a call for self-discipline in the contest.
Supporters would not forgive MPs who 'jeopardised' Mr Kinnock's
achievements, he said.
