<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Sterling stronger as shares add to gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING moved off the bottom of the European exchange rate mechanism for
the first time in five months yesterday.
The pound, buoyed by the re-election of the Conservative party, leapfrogged
the Danish krone to become the second weakest currency in the European
Monetary System.
Its better performance was due mainly to its own strength, but analysts said
the krone had weakened over fears that the country would vote against
European Monetary Union in a referendum to be held in early June.
Sterling and the dollar also strengthened against the D-Mark which came
under selling pressure. The pound closed at DM2.9150 compared with an
opening DM2.8988, putting it six pfennigs above its pre-election level and
within the 2.25 per cent fluctuation margin of the ERM.
Share prices advanced, lifting the FT-SE 100 index 18.4 to 2,591.0 for a
gain of more than 6 per cent since the election.
There was no sign of an early cut in interest rates.
Lex, Page 20
Currencies, Page 31
London stocks, Page 40
</TEXT>
