FT  14 APR 92 / Fresh approach urged for education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN END to the 'vivisection approach' to education policy, and a greater
willingness by parents to pay for school improvements, were yesterday urged
by the leader of a teaching union, Andrew Adonis writes.
Mrs Heather Ryan, president of the AMMA, told her union's annual conference
in Birmingham that teachers had 'been forced to breaking point' by the
government's 'muddled planning and impossible targets, rigidly imposed
without thought'.
She added: 'Politicians and Civil Service advisers have approached education
like vivisectionists, using schools as laboratories for doctrinaire
curriculum, assessment and funding techniques, squeezing the life and
creativity out of the education service.'
Mrs Ryan said AMMA, the third-largest teachers' union, would fight to retain
coursework in the GCSE exam and to secure a general teaching council for
England and Wales that would 'give teachers a right to influence government
on key issues on which we have the authority of our hard-won professional
expertise'.
