<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Air traffic stages modest recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK AIR traffic staged a very modest recovery in the first quarter of this
year after last year's slump caused by the Gulf war and the economic
recession.
Passenger traffic at airports in the south-east run by BAA, the airports
operator, increased by 19 per cent to 13.6m passengers in the first quarter,
against 11.4m in the same period last year at the height of the Gulf
conflict.
The BAA figures, published yesterday, show traffic increased by barely 1 per
cent compared with the first quarter of 1990. Passenger traffic last month
rose 12 per cent on March last year and was flat compared with March 1990.
The small recovery in passenger numbers compared with 1990 reflects the
continuing impact of the recession. Traffic at London's Heathrow airport has
shown the strongest improvement, but Gatwick is still struggling to recover
former passenger levels.
Traffic at Heathrow increased to 9.5m in the first quarter of this year from
7.7m in the same period last year and 9.2m in 1990. In contrast traffic at
Gatwick totalled 3.7m passengers in the first quarter of this year compared
with 3.5m last year and 4m in 1990.
Apart from the recession, Gatwick was hit by several airlines' decision to
transfer operations to Heathrow after the government last year scrapped
London air-traffic rules and opened access into Heathrow to all carriers.
Food at Heathrow has made impressive improvements during recent months,
while food at Charles de Gaulle airport in Paris is 'disastrous' and
'abysmal', according to a report by Mr Egon Ronay, the food critic.
A survey published yesterday by Mr Ronay's magazine said of the French
airport: 'How a nation which justly prides itself on its gastronomic prowess
could tolerate what we consider is disastrous food, particularly in an
international shop window, is beyond me.'
By contrast there had been a 'remarkable and commendable transformation' at
Heathrow after an unfavourable first report. 'It is heartening to see what
can be achieved after a none-too-gentle prod,' Mr Ronay said.
</TEXT>
