<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 92 / Japan reports monthly trade surplus of Dollars 11bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN yesterday reported a record monthly trade surplus of Dollars 10.98bn
(Pounds 6.3bn) for March, bringing the surplus for the full fiscal year to
Dollars 88.35bn, a 62.7 per cent increase and a potentially large source of
trade problems for the Japanese government.
The customs-cleared surplus for the year was close to the record of Dollars
89.7bn in fiscal 1986, and prompted Mr Kozo Watanabe, the trade and industry
minister, to promise to rekindle domestic growth in an attempt to halt the
expansion of exports.
Japan's economic slowdown was reflected in the 29.3 per cent increase in the
March surplus, as imports fell 8.2 per cent from a year earlier to Dollars
19.32bn, while exports rose 2.6 per cent to Dollars 30.30bn. Exports for the
year rose 8.1 per cent to Dollars 320.58bn, imports dipped 4.2 per cent to
Dollars 232.22bn.
The US Congress will note a marginal 1.2 per cent increase in Japanese
imports of US products and that the bilateral deficit rose for the first
time in five years, and query whether market opening measures have been
effective. The US deficit in bilateral trade last year was Dollars 38.46bn,
up from Dollars 38.12bn, following a 1.1 per cent increase in exports from
Japan.
However, the Ministry of Finance's seasonally adjusted figures showed that
the surge in surplus over the past few months could have peaked, with the
March surplus at Dollars 9.17bn, down from Dollars 10.43bn in February.
Exports decreased 3.8 per cent to Dollars 27.92bn, imports increased 0.9 per
cent to Dollars 18.75bn.
For the year, exports to the EC were 5.6 per cent higher at Dollars 59.76bn,
while Japan's imports from the EC declined 11.4 per cent to Dollars 31.32bn,
highlighted by a 14.3 per cent fall in imports from Italy and a 25.1 per
cent plunge in imports from France. Both countries' exports were hurt by the
slowing of demand for luxury products.
China became a lucrative market again last year for Japanese companies, with
exports 45.4 per cent higher at Dollars 9.42bn, and imports up 13.8 per cent
to Dollars 14.56bn. Exports to the rest of Asia rose 12.9 per cent to
Dollars 106.57bn and imports rose 4.1 per cent to Dollars 72.46bn.
Japan's trade with the newly industrialised economies of Asia, Singapore,
Hong Kong, Taiwan and South Korea now outstrips that with the EC. Exports to
those economies rose 13.1 per cent to Dollars 67.78bn, and imports were 4.7
per cent higher at Dollars 27.35bn.
The most significant increases in Japanese exports last year were in cars
(7.7 per cent), video cameras (16.1 per cent), semiconductor equipment (12.3
per cent) and ships (22.6 per cent). Japan's machinery imports rose by only
4 per cent, and imports of cars fell 20.4 per cent by value and 25.9 per
cent by volume.
</TEXT>
