FT  14 APR 92 / Cloves row gives Indonesian politics a shot in the arm:
Suharto's son replies to criticisms of monopoly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JAKARTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDONESIA'S governing political party, Golkar, has been publicly criticised
by Mr Hutomo Mandala Putra, a leading businessman and youngest son of
President Suharto.
The attack has given the country's political life a shot in the arm in
advance of June's general election.
Mr Putra, a majority shareholder of Humpuss Group Indonesia and chairman of
BPPC, a private agency with monopoly rights over the trading of cloves, was
responding to criticisms by senior Golkar figures of BPPC.
'The critics do not know what they are talking about,' Mr Putra told the
daily Media Indonesia at the weekend.
In the run-up to the election on June 9, local papers have identified the
monopoly as a key political issue. Golkar is widely expected to win the
election, but political pundits say the issue will test the bond between
party, the President, and his family. The Jakarta Post, a leading
English-language paper, has run two editorials within three weeks critical
of BPPC.
About 70,000 tonnes of cloves are sold each year to Indonesia's kretek
cigarette manufacturers.
Early this year, however, BPPC ran into financial trouble and the trade in
cloves ground to a halt.
Diplomats and donor officials say the monopoly runs counter to the
government's commitment to deregulation.
Mr Usman Hasan, the deputy secretary-general of Golkar, was reported as
saying BPPC should be closed down.
The agency has also been criticised by Mr Kharis Suhud, speaker of the House
of Representatives, who argues that it is hurting, not helping farmers.
Set up in 1990, BPPC has provided a floor price of Rp7,000 a kilo for
Indonesia's 3m to 4m clove farmers, twice the level of previous lows; the
agency sells on to the kretek manufacturers for about Rp12,500 per kilo.
Its problems stem from its current clove stock - 155,000 tonnes, equal to
two years production - and Mr Putra recently suggested that farmers should
burn half this year's crop to ease over-supply. BPPC officials have also
conceded that the agency will be unable to meet repayment terms on a Rp760bn
soft loan made in 1990 by the central bank.
Last week the government announced that BPPC would transfer much of the
cloves procurement to local co-operatives. The floor price would be lowered
by 7 per cent, and up to 49 per cent of the price would be retained by the
co-operatives in the form of equity funds and 'compulsory savings' for the
farmers.
BPPC will remain the exclusive supplier to kretek manufacturers, and Mr
Putra has said there will be no reduction in the selling price until its
current stock is exhausted.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
