FT  14 APR 92 / Bonn urged to come clean on finances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE German government was challenged yesterday to spell out clearly the
country's financial situation and urged to freeze public spending.
Publishing details of financial problems and their causes would make it
easier to persuade people of the need to economise, according to Prof
Hans-Jurgen Schmahl, head of the HWWA economics institute in Hamburg. The
condition of state finances was increasingly alarming, he said at the
presentation of a review by the country's five main economics institutes.
Companies and individuals faced increased social security contributions, he
claimed, because outgoings were outstripping income.
Describing the institutes' lowered forecast of 1 per cent growth in the west
this year as 'uncertain', he urged more pay claim moderation and
renegotiation of agreements guaranteeing most east German workers pay parity
with the west by the end of 1994.
